   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "84d63a3d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "Assumptions:\n",
    "    1. Linearity\n",
    "    2. No Multicolinearity\n",
    "    3. Normality\n",
    "    4. Homoscadasticity"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "b3ba252c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "y = m1x1+m2x2+....+mnxn+c"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "f3c8cf52",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\t1. Linearity:\n",
    "\t\ta. Every independent variable must have linear relationship with targeted variable.\n",
    "\t\tb. Can be checked using basic scatter plot\n",
    "        \n",
    "\t2. Very low/No multicollinearity:\n",
    "\t\ta. If independent variables have high correlation between each other then there exist multicollinearity between such variables which is unwanted.\n",
    "\t\tb. We check for the coefficient of x1(shift in y for every shift in x1) in eq: y=m1x1+m2x2….+mnxn+c, keeping all the other variables constant. Bt if independent variables are co related(say x1 & x2 are corelated) then for change in x1, x2 will also change & so shift in y for every shift in x1 will change from its true value bcz coefficients of x1 & x2 are inflicted.\n",
    "\t\tc. Can be checked using basic scatter plot\n",
    "        \n",
    "\t3. NO Heteroscedasticity:\n",
    "\t\ta. This happen when the data is not evenly spread across the best fit line.\n",
    "        \n",
    "\t4. No Auto-Correlations of errors with each other:\n",
    "\t\ta. It means that errors for every value of x should not be co-related to each other.\n",
    "\t\tb. If this happens then that means that our model is not capturing the underlying patter of data.\n",
    "        \n",
    "\t5. Normal distribution of errors:\n",
    "\t\ta. When the error are normally distributed & not vary scattered then it gives good predictions.\n",
    "\t\tb. Can be checked using QQ plot\n",
    "All observations( independent variables) are independent to each other."
   ]
  },
  {
